title: Data generation
text: first step, create dataset 1,000 patients 11 variables following distributions. following table illustrates odds exposure assignment. Fitting generalized linear model assessing probablity treatment assignment, constellation odds results following simulated distributions depicting propensities treatment initiation (aka propensity scores). Treatment assignment probabilities.
code: set.seed(seed_value)  # start with basic dataframe, covariates and their association with exposure sim_covar <- tibble::tibble(   exposure = rbinom(n = n, size = 1, prob = 0.4),   age_num = rnorm(n, mean = 64 - 5.5*exposure, sd = 13.7),   female_cat = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = 0.39 - 0.12*exposure),   ecog_cat = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = 0.63 - 0.08*exposure),   smoking_cat = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = 0.15 + 0.1*exposure),    egfr_cat = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = 0.10 + 0.2*exposure),    kras_cat = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = 0.07 + 0.05*exposure),   histology_is_squamous_cat = rbinom(n, size = 1, prob = 0.2),   ldl_num = rnorm(n, mean = 115.1, sd = 41.1), # cholesterol   rr_num = rnorm(n, mean = 123.7, sd = 20.6), # systolic blood pressure   bpm_num = rnorm(n, mean = 74.2, sd = 11.7) # heart rate   ) %>%     # bring data in right format   dplyr::mutate(across(ends_with("num"), as.numeric)) %>%    dplyr::mutate(across(ends_with("num"), function(x) round(x, digits = 2))) sim_covar %>%    gtsummary::tbl_summary(by = "exposure") %>%    gtsummary::add_difference() exposure_form <- as.formula(paste("exposure ~ ", paste(colnames(sim_covar %>% dplyr::select(-exposure)), collapse = " + ")))  exposure_fit <- stats::glm(   exposure_form,   data = sim_covar,   family = "binomial"   )  exposure_fit %>%    gtsummary::tbl_regression(exponentiate = T) # compute propensity score exposure_plot <- sim_covar %>%    dplyr::mutate(ps = fitted(exposure_fit))  # plot density exposure_plot %>%    ggplot2::ggplot(ggplot2::aes(x = ps, fill = factor(exposure))) +   ggplot2::geom_density(alpha = .5) +   ggplot2::theme_bw() +   ggplot2::labs(     x = "Pr(exposure)",     y = "Density",     fill = "Exposed"   )

title: Data generation
text: Next, simulate time--event outcome overall survival. , simsurv package used following assumptions: Parametric event times follow exponential distribution Max event times: 2 years follow-Event times depend (time-fixed/baseline) covariate effects listed table HR(exposure) = 0.7 HR(EGFR) = 0.5 (strong prognostic factor)
code: betas_os <- c(   exposure = log(0.7),   age_num = log(1.05),   female_cat = log(0.9),   ecog_cat = log(1.2),   smoking_cat = log(1.3),   egfr_cat = log(0.5),   kras_cat = log(0.95),   histology_is_squamous_cat = log(1.15),   ldl_num = log(1.01),   rr_num = log(1.05),   bpm_num = log(1.005)   )  betas_os %>%    as.data.frame() %>%    tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "Covariate") %>%    gt::gt() set.seed(seed_value)  sim_df <- sim_covar %>% dplyr::bind_cols(   simsurv::simsurv(     dist = "exponential",     lambdas = 0.00005,     betas = betas_os,     x = sim_covar,     maxt = 2     )   ) %>%    dplyr::mutate(id = paste0("ENROL", id)) %>%    dplyr::relocate(id, .before = exposure)

title: NARFCS sensitivity analysis
text: seen earlier, missingness mechanism important covariate, strong partially observed confounder, truly follows either missing completely random (MCAR) missing random value (MNAR[value]) scenario, distinction two can turn difficult. can serious consequences since covariates follow true MNAR(value) mechanism may severely bias effect estimation exposure interest. reality, able know 100% true missingness mechanism may always residual uncertainty case MNAR(value). positive side, however, Leacy Moreno-Betancur et al.1 proposed useful procedure impute multivariable missing data MNAR(value) conditions. definition, MNAR(value) mechanism, true (unobserved) values variable systematically differ observed values. idea random fully conditional specification (NARFCS) sensitivity analysis specify imputation model containing sensitivity parameter 𝛅 reflects systematic departure missing random (MAR) mechanism.

title: NARFCS sensitivity analysis
text: example, age patients certain age cut-may systematically less frequently recorded. Despite , age may still important predictor initiation treatment interest simultaneously import prognostic variable outcome (death due reason example). now, don’t assume missing covariates. order introduce MNAR(value) mechanism age covariate, : Determine missingess pattern, age set missing Create weight vector, age (non-zero value) linear predictor probability observations becoming missing. specify type logistic probabillity distribution missingness weights, cases low weighted sum scores (.e. younger age) larger probability becoming incomplete. missingness probability ~40%
code: # load data and drop id column smdi_data <- smdi::smdi_data %>%    dplyr::select(-id)  # determine missingness pattern age_col <- which(colnames(smdi_data)=="age_num") miss_pattern <- rep(1, ncol(smdi_data)) miss_pattern_age <- replace(miss_pattern, age_col, 0)  # weights to compute missingness probability # covariate itself is only predictor miss_weights_mnar_v <- rep(0, ncol(smdi_data)) miss_weights_mnar_v <- replace(miss_weights_mnar_v, age_col, 1)  miss_prop_age <- .4  set.seed(42) smdi_mnar_v <- mice::ampute(   data = smdi_data,   prop = miss_prop_age,   mech = "MNAR",   patterns = miss_pattern_age,   weights = miss_weights_mnar_v,   bycases = TRUE,   type = "LEFT"   )

title: NARFCS sensitivity analysis
text: plot direct comparison age distributions original data data complete cases removing missing value following MNAR(value) mechanism, can observe systematic difference two datasets,
code: smdi_data_mnar_v <- smdi_mnar_v$amp  dplyr::bind_rows(   smdi_data %>% dplyr::select(age_num) %>% dplyr::mutate(dataset = "Complete"),   smdi_data_mnar_v %>% dplyr::select(age_num) %>% dplyr::mutate(dataset = "MNAR(value)")   ) %>%    ggplot2::ggplot(ggplot2::aes(x = dataset, y = age_num)) +   ggplot2::geom_violin() +   ggplot2::geom_boxplot(width = 0.3) +   ggplot2::labs(     y = "Age [years]",     x = "Cohort"   ) +   ggplot2::theme_bw()

title: NARFCS sensitivity analysis
text: can now compare estimate estimated bias caused 40% MNAR(value) missing values. First, specify general outcome model. Next, compute true Hazard Ratio (HR), complete case HR standard mice multiple imputation HR.  can observe, complete case analysis slightly overestimates true treatment effect multiple imputation approach slightly underestimates . However, confidence intervals highly overlapping bias limited given rather weak/moderate association age exposure (~ 0.97) age outcome (~ HR 1.05).
code: # outcome model (see data generation script) cox_lhs <- "survival::Surv(eventtime, status)" covariates <- smdi::smdi_data %>%    dplyr::select(-c(id, exposure, eventtime, status)) %>%    names() cox_rhs <- paste(covariates, collapse = " + ") cox_form <- as.formula(paste(cox_lhs, "~ exposure +", cox_rhs))  cox_form   #> survival::Surv(eventtime, status) ~ exposure + age_num + female_cat +  #>     ecog_cat + smoking_cat + egfr_cat + kras_cat + histology_is_squamous_cat +  #>     ldl_num + rr_num + bpm_num # true outcome model cox_fit_true <- survival::coxph(cox_form, data = smdi::smdi_data) %>%    broom::tidy(exponentiate = TRUE, conf.int = TRUE) %>%    dplyr::filter(term == "exposure") %>%    dplyr::select(term, estimate, conf.low, conf.high, std.error) %>%    dplyr::mutate(analysis = "True estimate")   # complete case analysis cox_fit_cc <- survival::coxph(cox_form, data = smdi_data_mnar_v) %>%    broom::tidy(exponentiate = TRUE, conf.int = TRUE) %>%    dplyr::filter(term == "exposure") %>%    dplyr::select(term, estimate, conf.low, conf.high, std.error) %>%    dplyr::mutate(analysis = "Complete case analysis")  # Multiple imputation (predictive mean matching) cox_fit_imp <- mice::mice(   data = smdi_data_mnar_v,   seed = 42,    print = FALSE   ) %>%   with(     expr = survival::coxph(formula(paste(format(cox_form), collapse = "")))     ) %>%    mice::pool() %>%    summary(conf.int = TRUE, exponentiate = TRUE) %>%    dplyr::filter(term == "exposure") %>%    dplyr::select(term, estimate, conf.low = `2.5 %`, conf.high = `97.5 %`, std.error) %>%    dplyr::mutate(analysis = "Multiple imputation")  forest <- dplyr::bind_rows(cox_fit_true, cox_fit_cc, cox_fit_imp) %>%    dplyr::mutate(analysis = factor(analysis, levels = c("True estimate", "Complete case analysis", "Multiple imputation"))) %>%    ggplot2::ggplot(ggplot2::aes(y = forcats::fct_rev(analysis))) +   ggplot2::geom_point(ggplot2::aes(x = estimate), shape = 15, size = 3) +   ggplot2::geom_errorbar(ggplot2::aes(xmin = conf.low, xmax = conf.high)) +   ggplot2::geom_vline(xintercept = cox_fit_true[[2]], linetype = "dashed") +   ggplot2::labs(x = "Hazard Ratio", y= "") +   ggplot2::theme_bw()  table <- dplyr::bind_rows(cox_fit_true, cox_fit_cc, cox_fit_imp) %>%    dplyr::select(-term) %>%    dplyr::relocate(analysis, .before = estimate) %>%    dplyr::mutate(dplyr::across(tidyselect::where(is.numeric), ~round(.x, 2)))  gridExtra::grid.arrange(gridExtra::tableGrob(table, rows = NULL), forest)

Hence, continuous covariates (like example) difference mean conditional female_cat + ecog_cat + smoking_cat + egfr_cat + kras_cat + histology_is_squamous_cat + ldl_num + rr_num + bpm_num. reality, know sensitivity parameter, easily plug NARFCS.
code: mean <- mean(smdi_data$age_num) - mean(smdi_data_mnar_v$age_num, na.rm = TRUE) mean #> [1] -5.144647 # initialize method vector method_vector <- rep("", ncol(smdi_data_mnar_v))                      # columns for narfcs imputation with sensitivity parameter mnar_imp_method <- which(colnames(smdi_data_mnar_v) == "age_num")  # update method vector method_vector <- replace(x = method_vector, list = c(mnar_imp_method), values = c("mnar.norm"))  # mnar model specification mnar_blot <- list(age_num = list(ums = toString(mean)))  narfcs_imp <- mice::mice(   data = smdi_data_mnar_v,   method = method_vector,   blots = mnar_blot,   seed = 42,    print = FALSE   ) %>%    with(     expr = survival::coxph(formula(paste(format(cox_form), collapse = "")))     ) %>%    mice::pool() %>%    summary(conf.int = TRUE, exponentiate = TRUE) %>%    dplyr::filter(term == "exposure") %>%    dplyr::select(term, estimate, conf.low = `2.5 %`, conf.high = `97.5 %`, std.error) %>%    dplyr::mutate(analysis = "NARFCS imputation")  forest <- dplyr::bind_rows(cox_fit_true, cox_fit_cc, cox_fit_imp, narfcs_imp) %>%    dplyr::mutate(analysis = factor(analysis, levels = c("True estimate", "Complete case analysis", "Multiple imputation", "NARFCS imputation"))) %>%    ggplot2::ggplot(ggplot2::aes(y = forcats::fct_rev(analysis), color = ifelse(analysis == "NARFCS imputation", 'red', 'black'))) +   ggplot2::geom_point(ggplot2::aes(x = estimate), shape = 15, size = 3) +   ggplot2::geom_errorbar(ggplot2::aes(xmin = conf.low, xmax = conf.high)) +   ggplot2::geom_vline(xintercept = cox_fit_true[[2]], linetype = "dashed") +   ggplot2::labs(x = "Hazard Ratio", y= "") +   ggplot2::scale_color_identity() +   ggplot2::theme_bw()  forest

title: NARFCS sensitivity analysis
text: unfortunately, reality don’t know value 𝛅. Nevertheless, want make sure whatever analytical decision chose primary analysis (complete case approach imputation approach), results drastically change true underlying missingness mechanism MNAR(value). NARFCS sensitivity analysis comes handy also often used tipping point analysis, .e. model multiple NARFCS-specified imputation models range 𝛅 sensitivity parameters evaluate pre-specified 𝛅, confidence interval cross certain estimate threshold discard qualitative conclusion main analysis.
code: # modeled over a range of deltas narfcs_modeled <- function(i){      # mnar model specification ('i' is delta parameter)   mnar_blot <- list(age_num = list(ums = paste(i)))    narfcs_imp <- mice::mice(     data = smdi_data_mnar_v,     method = method_vector,     blots = mnar_blot,     seed = 42,      print = FALSE     ) %>%      with(       expr = survival::coxph(formula(paste(format(cox_form), collapse = "")))       ) %>%      mice::pool() %>%      summary(conf.int = TRUE, exponentiate = TRUE) %>%      dplyr::filter(term == "exposure") %>%      dplyr::select(term, estimate, conf.low = `2.5 %`, conf.high = `97.5 %`, std.error) %>%      dplyr::mutate(delta = i)    }   narfcs_range <- lapply(   X = seq(-10, 10, 1),   FUN = narfcs_modeled   )  narfcs_range_df <- do.call(rbind, narfcs_range)  reference_lines <- tibble::tibble(   yintercept = c(1, cox_fit_true[[2]]),   Reference = c("H0 rejection", "True HR"),   color = c("red", "darkgreen") )  narfcs_range_df %>%    ggplot2::ggplot(ggplot2::aes(x = delta, y = estimate)) +   ggplot2::geom_point() +   ggplot2::geom_line() +   ggplot2::geom_ribbon(ggplot2::aes(ymin = conf.low, ymax = conf.high), alpha = 0.15) +   ggplot2::labs(x = "Sensitivity parameter δ", y = "Hazard ratio (95% CI)") +   ggplot2::scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(-10, 10, 1), limits = c(-10, 10)) +   ggplot2::geom_hline(ggplot2::aes(yintercept = yintercept, color = Reference), reference_lines) +   ggplot2::scale_colour_manual(values = reference_lines$color) +   ggplot2::theme_bw() +   ggplot2::theme(legend.position="top")

text: many different quantitative disciplines classic epidemiology machine deep learning increasing interest utilizing electronic health records (EHR) develop prognostic/predictive models study comparative effectiveness safety medical interventions. Especially information variables readily available datasets (e.g. administrative claims) high interest, including vital signs, biomarkers lab data. However, covariates often just partially observed various reasons: Physician perform/order certain test Certain measurements just collected particularly sick patients Information ‘hiding’ unstructured records, e.g. clinical notes illustrate smdi's main functionalities, introduce missingness relevant covariates (e.g. egfr_cat biomarker covariate) critical confounders causal exposure-outcome relationship smdi_data dataset. : insert DAG confounder relationship introduce missingness, use ampute function mice package. excellent tutorial flexible elegant function can found .

title: Routine structural missing data diagnostics
text: Eastern Cooperative Oncology Group (ECOG) performance score clinical measure cancer disease affects daily living abilities patient often used patient inclusion criterion clinical trials. scale ranges 0 5 typically patients 0 1 eligible. Let’s assume example, already subset pre-selected clinical trial-like cohort, still want adjust baseline ECOG 0 1 (definitions taken 1): ECOG = 0: Fully active, able carry pre-disease performance without restriction ECOG = 1: Restricted physically strenuous activity ambulatory able carry work light sedentary nature, e.g., light house work, office work Since know patients eligible ECOG either 0 1, data managers mindful entering information EHR others recorded information. typical example variable missing completely random neither ECOG variable observed unobserved covariates related missingness. : insert DAG missingness-confounder relationship can see, around 30% ECOG observations missing now.
code: # discard patient ID variable smdi_data <- smdi::smdi_data %>%    dplyr::select(-id)    # specify missingness pattern # (0 = set to missing, 1 = remains complete) # the pattern is the same for all scenarios miss_pattern <- rep(1, ncol(smdi_data)) ecog_col <- which(colnames(smdi_data)=="ecog_cat") miss_pattern_ecog <- replace(miss_pattern, ecog_col, 0) miss_prop_ecog <- .3  set.seed(42) smdi_data_mcar <- mice::ampute(   data = smdi_data,   prop = miss_prop_ecog,   mech = "MCAR",   patterns = miss_pattern_ecog,   bycases = TRUE   )$amp  smdi_data_mcar %>%    dplyr::select(exposure, ecog_cat) %>%    gtsummary::tbl_summary(by = "exposure") %>%    gtsummary::add_overall() %>%    gtsummary::add_difference()

title: Routine structural missing data diagnostics
code: smoking_col <- which(colnames(smdi_data)=="smoking_cat") miss_pattern_smoking <- replace(miss_pattern, smoking_col, 0)  # weights to compute missingness probability # all covariates contribute equally (of course except smoking itself) miss_weights_mar <- rep(1, ncol(smdi_data)) miss_weights_mar <- replace(miss_weights_mar, smoking_col, 0)  miss_prop_smoking <- .15  set.seed(42) smdi_data_mar <- mice::ampute(   data = smdi_data,   prop = miss_prop_smoking,   mech = "MAR",   patterns = miss_pattern_smoking,   weights = miss_weights_mar,   bycases = TRUE   )$amp  smdi_data_mar %>%    dplyr::select(exposure, smoking_cat) %>%    gtsummary::tbl_summary(by = "exposure") %>%    gtsummary::add_overall() %>%    gtsummary::add_difference()

title: Routine structural missing data diagnostics
code: age_col <- which(colnames(smdi_data)=="age_num") miss_pattern_age <- replace(miss_pattern, age_col, 0)  # weights to compute missingness probability # covariate itself is only predictor miss_weights_mnar_v <- rep(0, ncol(smdi_data)) miss_weights_mnar_v <- replace(miss_weights_mnar_v, age_col, 1)  miss_prop_age <- .4  set.seed(42) smdi_data_mnar_v <- mice::ampute(   data = smdi_data,   prop = miss_prop_age,   mech = "MNAR",   patterns = miss_pattern_age,   weights = miss_weights_mnar_v,   bycases = TRUE,   type = "RIGHT"   )$amp  smdi_data_mnar_v %>%    dplyr::select(exposure, age_num) %>%    gtsummary::tbl_summary(by = "exposure") %>%    gtsummary::add_overall() %>%    gtsummary::add_difference() df <- smdi::smdi_data %>%    dplyr::select(-c(ecog_cat, smoking_cat, age_num)) %>%    dplyr::bind_cols(ecog_cat = smdi_data_mcar$ecog_cat, smoking_cat = smdi_data_mar$smoking_cat, age_num = smdi_data_mnar_v$age_num) %>%    mutate(across(ends_with("cat"), as.factor)) %>%    select(-id)
